Clubs approve second Euro competition 
England, France and Wales could have 12 teams each in European
competitions next season if plans proposed on Friday are endorsed by
the countries' Unions.
Representatives of the first division clubs of England, Wales,
Scotland, Ireland, France and Italy all expressed their support for a
second competition in a meeting here.
In addition to the main European Cup, there will be a second tournament
involving teams from all six countries.
England, Wales and France, who will have four representatives in the
European Cup, will each have eight sides in the second competition.
Scotland and Ireland's three European Cup sides will be joined by a
further five in the subsidiary tournament.
And Italy, who have two sides in the European Cup, will enter another
two in the second competition.
